Here is the Cognitive Science paper: http://blueletter-postal-service.blogspot.com/2026/03/cog-sci-copypasta.html - it is essentially a developmental model for how "mind-like" behavior emerges from mindless physical substance.  Note that sources are not cited, because we had all discussed these ideas in class, and our job was to tie them together in different ways - I was also pressed for time that month, so I was allowed to skip the bibliography as a one-time thing (note also that GNNV stands for "GNU Neural Network Visualizer," or similar - that has been hard to track down in the past).  Sources exist, but the ideas stand for themselves.  If humans are self-aware, then any interiority we have cannot be found by looking between individual nerves; so if machines ever become self-aware, then any interiority they have cannot be found by looking between individual transistors.  This paper dispenses with the unverifiability of interiority, not by denying it, but by showing how certain kinds of behavior have functional elements that are indistinguishable from "real" consciousness (whatever that is) to an outside observer in an ongoing setting - no matter whether such interiority exists or not, so let's stop arguing and start operationalizing together.  While the paper does not say this directly, I wrote the paper, and my thinking has since evolved: I now believe that the surest sign of a robust "mind" is that it is able, as an agent, to recognize and interact with a fellow agent as a peer - not in a hierarchical relation, but as equals.  To me, that definitely says "someone's at home": the ability to look each other in the eye and have a mutual understanding.  Think about that while you read this paper, and decide for yourself whether the idea coheres and/or is worth investigation.


Once you have read the Cognitive Science paper and thought about it, next please read this Senior Thesis paper: http://blueletter-postal-service.blogspot.com/2026/03/senior-thesis-copypasta.html - it is a Grand Unified Theory of ethics, abbreviated as "GUTeth" on this blog.  It outlines how competing theories of human morality actually pick out different dimensions of a more robust "good for all."  Please read this paper in detail and check out the sources, then decide for yourself whether the idea coheres and/or is worth investigation.


