Paper 2: "Towards a Grand Unified Theory of Ethics: Long-sighted Self-effacing Consequentialism"

DEADNAME, Senior Thesis, Fall 2011 — Philosophy

What the paper argues, in order:

The paper aims to sketch a survey of ethics and articulate a unified consequentialist theory explaining historical disagreement between normative theories in light of recent neuroscience. Our moral intuitions pick out genuine goods and bads, but are often wrong — they aim at long-term benefits by indirect means that betray their ad hoc evolutionary origins.

Section 1 — Three theories:

Virtue ethics (Aristotle) provides role models and moral lessons; virtuous character is a hexis rather than mere habit. Kant adds rational universalizability — duties apply to all creatures with moral dignity. Consequentialism steps in where rules lead to bad outcomes. The self-effacing consequentialist believes consequences remain paramount, but better consequences are more reliably achieved by thinking like deontologists or virtue theorists.

Section 2 — The three-axis model (GUTeth):

All three theories pick out a real aspect of intuitive goodness: deontological judgments pick out fairness, virtue judgments pick out valuable character traits, and consequentialist judgments pick out outcomes. These can be plotted on three axes in a moral idea space. There is a line along which all three theories are in simultaneous agreement — an "axis of agreement" — and moral dilemmas occupy the "border regions" where theories diverge. Fairness, consequences, and virtues are relativistic in the way velocity judgments are relativistic — there is no absolute frame, but they are nonetheless real.

Section 3 — Neuroscience grounding:

The theory predicts that when moral dilemmas pit one normative theory against another, different brain processes should be at work. Greene's fMRI research on trolley problems is cited as consistent with this. The halo effect (Thorndike), height-based character perceptions (Persico), status-based height distortion (Wilson), and decision fatigue (Vohs) are cited as evidence that moral intuitions are pre-rational heuristics — imperfect evolutionary starting points.

Section 4 — Objections answered:

To "is any of this really good?": imagine a civilization that is fair, cultivates virtue, and in which everyone prospers — any theory that would call this less than good is "profoundly broken." On the organ-harvest trolley problem, the paper bites the bullet — within the thought experiment's terms, harvesting the organs is right because it is stipulated to yield the best consequences. Our revulsion simply shows that our intuitions evolved for our world, not for stipulated counterfactuals.

