1. The dialectic with virtue ethicists and Kantians is not fully closed.

Saying "virtues and duties are instrumentally valuable for producing good consequences" effectively converts the other theories into consequentialism's sub-contractors, which is not neutral. A serious virtue ethicist would push back: Aristotle's hexis is not a heuristic; it's constitutive of what it means to be a good person, full stop.

2. The organ-harvest bullet-biting is the most interesting moment, and also the least satisfying.

Within the paper's own three-axis framework, a non-consensual organ harvest should score poorly on both the fairness axis (treating a moral agent as a mere means) and the virtue axis (a doctor who does this is not trustworthy). The paper doesn't run its own GUTeth model on its own counterexample — it retreats to pure single-axis consequentialism, undercutting the pluralism it has been building.

3. The figures are missing.

Three figures are referenced throughout and are clearly doing important work to make the three-axis model visually tractable. Without them, the spatial metaphor has to be reconstructed entirely from text.

4. The neuroscience section has aged unevenly.

The height/status studies (particularly Wilson 1968) and decision fatigue research (Vohs) have faced significant replication challenges. The paper presents these as more settled than they now appear. The Greene fMRI work has held up better, but even that literature is more contested than the paper suggests.

